<br>
The bottom line is a government requires a certain amount of capital to perform the necessary functions of, well, governance, plus the cash to carry out its will - after these two requirements, a government attempts to keep a treasury and war chest available for use when needed.<br>
<br>
This capital does not magically appear, and taxes are the amount the citizenry contributes which keeps a way of life sustainable - one can argue endlessly regarding exactly *how much* is required to perform precisely *what* but it more than a bit  naive to rail flatly against the notion of taxes and simply asinine to deny a need for capital to fund the auspices of government.<br>
<br>
Bottom Line:  While the IRS has a lot of problems, is one of the most corrupt branches of the US government and is plagued by staff either the incompetent or simply malicious, this does not relieve you of your tax obligations for money earned in the US - pay up.  Oh, and watch me get audited this year. =P <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/ubaruchthebarbarianbastard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>baruch the barbarian bastard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#ffffff>(9/12/02 6:10:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3519.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Income Taxes, please read</span><hr size=1> Yes, taxes are necessary to fund the tangled mess of government spending. But why, my friend, is there such a mess? <br>
<br>
Ascertain the answer by looking over a succinct list of government expendetures. Billions of taxpayer dollars are lost on unnessecary programs. Examples are too numerous to indulge on an EverQuest board, but I'll cite my favorite ones-the bloated EPA and the corrupt welfare system (insert your &quot;I Hate Reaganites&quot; comment at will, I don't care)-as two our government ought to stop funding immediately. <br>
<br>
Ultimately, our country was founded on the principles of recognizing the rights of man. As Locke pointed out, the arbitrary use of force on another, whether by government or by person, violates those innate rights. Income taxes are involuntarily taken from us, and, whether the intentions are good or bad, that constitutes an initiation of force by the government, and therefore a violation of our innate rights. <br>
<br>
The question of where the country would get the funds should income taxes be revoked is a dire misdirection. The policies themselves must be studied and cleaned out-and, after such a purge, personal income taxes would not be needed. <br>
<br>
A proper government should exist only to protect the rights of its citizens from the initiation of force. At the core, this means funding police for protection at home, an army for protection abroad, and the judicial/congressional/executive branches for managing and enforcing specific laws. The cost of this government is very, very small compared to the  hippopotamus in place today. <br>
<br>
If you're a liberal feeler-feeler type, and your motive isn't truly inclined towards larger governmnet, only the well-being of others-don't fret. If a government doesn't fund welfare or education, those institutions will still exist through charities and private practice. Their costs will reduce substatially, and their management and quality will shoot through the roof. The result is a better educated citizen who is helped only in a time of need and pushed hard to work and excel to the limit of his abilities. <br>
<br>
Even though it's in the Constitution itself, I personally feel that, ironically, income tax is unconstitutional. History shows that the idea had been struck down again and again by the Supreme Court, but the irritated Congress, hungry for money, bypassed this little problem by slipping it in as an amendment in 1913. How is it unconstitutional? Check the thirteenth amendment-one cannot avoid the fact that the time spent earning the money taken by the government represents time spent in involuntary servitude. <br>
<br>
Word. <br>
